  "response_text": "The cumulative count of skimmed or semi-skimmed milk choices begins at approximately zero at the initial time step. During the first five time steps, the metric exhibits slow growth, accumulating roughly 1,000 to 1,500 total choices. Between time steps 5 and 10, the rate of increase accelerates substantially, with the cumulative total rising to approximately 5,000 choices. After time step 10, the growth trajectory becomes approximately linear, increasing at a rate of roughly 800 to 1,000 choices per time step. By the final time step (approximately step 32), the cumulative total reaches approximately 25,000 to 26,000 choices.\n\nAcross the simulation runs, the trajectories remain tightly clustered, with the dispersion between runs increasing modestly over time. At the conclusion, the spread between the maximum and minimum values across runs is approximately 1,000 choices, representing about 4% of the final cumulative value.\n\nThese dynamics indicate a classic diffusion process: the initial period of slow accumulation reflects limited early adoption of skimmed and semi-skimmed milk varieties when whole milk dominated the market. The acceleration phase between steps 5 and 10 corresponds to a period of rapid behavioral transition, where social influence and changing perceptions drove increasing numbers of agents to switch from whole milk to lower-fat alternatives. The subsequent linear growth at a rate approaching the theoretical maximum of 1,000 choices per step (equivalent to all 1,000 agents selecting skimmed or semi-skimmed milk at each decision point) indicates that by approximately step 10 to 15, adoption had reached near-saturation levels. In the later time steps, the vast majority of agents consistently choose skimmed or semi-skimmed varieties, resulting in the steady linear accumulation of approximately one choice per agent per time step. The consistency across multiple simulation runs suggests that the model produces robust outcomes for this parameter configuration, with stochastic variation in network interactions and individual dispositions generating only minor deviations in the aggregate adoption trajectory."
